This is a good and easy course and prof really did a good job on not exposing too much material to the students with very limited math maturity&hellip;
It reviews a lot on the material studied in first/second year calculus. The new material is roughly \(\subseteq \textbf{PMATH 333} \cup \textbf{PMATH 351} \), and some dynamic system, and possibly some computational math.
The prof used ROUNDUP in final mark calculation: \(91.1\to 92 \). Wish it could be applied to other courses&hellip;

This midterm was brutal&hellip; avg was about 65&hellip; and last term was about 78, and added 3 marks for everyone&hellip;
The material (reduction, algorithms, complexity theory) is pretty standard and straightforward if you have a good prof like in Fall 2019.
The notes above is generated from Spring 2021 offering.

Taught by Penny, Cambridge PhD.
Content is hard, assignments are hard, while tests are ok. But if you can&rsquo;t get the test questions after the first look, you won&rsquo;t have time to finish them&hellip;
She will be teaching 442 next term (Fall 2019).

Taught by a PhD student, Ali. Bonus is great: attend to 5 short quizzes, then you get 5 marks.
This course is math heavy (compared to cs 370, which is programming heavy). The content is a bit disorganized&hellip;
These notes cover numerical methods and computational mathematics. Topics include floating-point arithmetic and error analysis, root finding (bisection, fixed point, Newton&rsquo;s method), numerical linear algebra (Gaussian elimination, LU factorization, condition numbers), polynomial interpolation (Lagrange, Hermite, splines), numerical integration (trapezoidal, Simpson&rsquo;s, Gaussian quadrature), and the discrete Fourier transform.

This course is taught by a single instructor all over the terms. Some said it&rsquo;s easy to get 98&hellip; I am not sure why she gave me such a low mark&hellip;
Anyway, just prepare the slides and textbooks before the final&hellip;
Here is my presentation.
Also, we were required to submit a book review. I chose China in Ten Words by Yu Hua. Here is the reflection.

Dave again&hellip; In the last lecture of cs 135, he introduced imperative paradigm with Racket. However, Racket session in cs 136 was chopped since cs 136 is for all math students, or Racket is not that useful later on if you don&rsquo;t do research on programming languages (check cs 442).
It&rsquo;s the second time he used that Chinese joke again. For the third time (cs 136 in Spring 2018), he didn&rsquo;t check the grammar of the Google Translate output, so the result is weird&hellip;
English is your:
A) First Language B) Second Language C) Third (or higher) Language D) 那件丑陋衬衫上的胖子说了什么？
See Course Website
Remarks This course is not that hard if you have a little background, like using for loops to draw rainbow&hellip; It has similar structure as cs 135: starts off slowly and carefully, and ramps up later in the term. I would say you will learn much much much more if you take cs 146: hard midterms, hard assignments, massive curve. You will learn some baby baby compilers&hellip;
